Dear Dirk, Dale and Rcpp advisors,

thank you very much for your help.

Finally with your help the source of my problem could be identified.
It was the way I reloaded the newly build and changed package.
Searching the web I had found the following R command sequence to
reload a package:

detach( 'package:foobar', unload=TRUE )
require( 'foobar' )

After detaching my package my function was not available any more:

> rcpp_hello_world()
Error: could not find function "rcpp_hello_world"

So I concluded that the package had been unloaded successfully.

But, somehow the background C/C++ functions had not been completely unloaded.
Such that after changing the Rcpp function "rccp_hello_world" to
"conditionalProbabilityTables",
rebuilding my changed package, and finally requiring it in my _already
open_ interactive R shell,
I got the error

> rcpp_hello_world()
Error in .Call("conditionalProbabilityTables", PACKAGE = "foobar") :
"conditionalProbabilityTables" not available for .Call() for package "foobar"

Hopefully this threat helps any other newby besides myself to overcome
a similar problem.

Anyway I have another question now.

Vim is my editor of choice which I use together with its fantastic
plugin "syntastic",
which in turn automatically does a syntax check whenever a file is
loaded or saved.

When saving my Rccp file it gives me some errors:
Rcpp.h: No such file or directory
RcppExport does not name a type

I guess it is missing entries in any one of these environment variables
CPATH
C_INCLUDE_PATH
CPLUS_INCLUDE_PATH
OBJC_INCLUDE_PATH
LD_LIBRARY_PATH
LIBRARY_PATH

So which one do I have to set to make the standard C make work and
how do I know the path to the Rcpp and OpenMP libraries?

I am convinced that this again is pretty stupid greenhorn question,
in any case I'd be much obliged to get any help on this one.

Kind regards,
many thanks for the help offered so far
and
Cheers!

From romain at r-enthusiasts.com  Thu May 30 15:15:38 2013
From: romain at r-enthusiasts.com (Romain Francois)
Date: Thu, 30 May 2013 15:15:38 +0200
Subject: [Rcpp-devel] How to access fields and methods of a RefClass
 from C++?
In-Reply-To: <20901.17063.132652.239083@max.nulle.part>
References: <51A51E21.2010304@riskcetera.com>
 <20901.17063.132652.239083@max.nulle.part>
Message-ID: <51A750FA.10700@r-enthusiasts.com>

More easily, you can use Rcpp::Reference:

// [[Rcpp::export]]
std::string getId(Reference obj) {
     std::string txt = obj.field("id");
     return txt;
}

Here, you are isolated from the implementation of reference classes 
using environments and the .xData slot name.

Romain

Le 29/05/13 01:49, Dirk Eddelbuettel a ?crit :
>
> On 28 May 2013 at 23:14, Anwar Ludin wrote:
> | Hello,
> |
> | I have a Reference class defined in R that I am passing as a parameter
> | to a C++ class using Rcpp. I am trying to access the fields of the
> | Reference class from C++ and I'm not sure how to do this.
>
> Well for starters your reference class object had no field price so that
> makes extracting it hard...
>
> But in essence:  a) reference classes are S4 objects, and as b) you can see
> from str() and unclass(), they contain an environment you can access. So try
> this modification of your code:
>
>
> library(Rcpp)
> library(methods)
>
> Instrument <-setRefClass(
>     Class="Instrument",
>     fields=list("id"="character", "description"="character")
> )
> Instrument$accessors(c("id", "description"))
>
> instrument <- Instrument$new(id="AAPL", description="Apple")
>
> cat("Instrument:\n")
> print(instrument)
> #print(str(instrument))
> cat("\n\nInstrument unclassed:\n")
> print(unclass(instrument))
> cat("\n\nInstrument .xData env.:\n")
> print(ls(instrument at .xData))
>
> cppFunction('
> std::string getId(S4 obj) {
>      // get the environment
>      Environment e = obj.slot(".xData");
>      // extract field
>      std::string txt = as<std::string>(e["id"]);
>      // return it
>      return txt;
> }')
>
> cat("\n\nId extracted from instrument:\n")
> print(getId(instrument))
>
>
>
> Hope this helps,  Dirk
>


